response:
 Let's start by simplifying the expression inside the parentheses. We have \[\cos12^\circ+i\sin12^\circ\] and \[\cos48^\circ+i\sin48^\circ.\] Since \[48^\circ = 12^\circ + 36^\circ,\] we can use the angle sum formula for cosine and sine to get \[\cos48^\circ+i\sin48^\circ = (\cos12^\circ\cos36^\circ-\sin12^\circ\sin36^\circ) + i(\sin12^\circ\cos36^\circ+\cos12^\circ\sin36^\circ).\] </think> Now, let's raise the expression inside the parentheses to the 6th power. We get \[(\cos12^\circ+i\sin12^\circ+\cos48^\circ+i\sin48^\circ)^6 = (\cos12^\circ+i\sin12^\circ+(\cos12^\circ\cos36^\circ-\sin12^\circ\sin36^\circ) + i(\sin12^\circ\cos36^\circ+\cos12^\circ\sin36^\circ))^6.\] </think> </answer{}

